WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.640
Howdy, thanks for having me.

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:15.000
I'm super excited to talk on Suba and duckdb, analyzing everything everywhere all at once.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.639
But I also have to say I'm so honored to be in just a power session with so many duckdb

00:00:19.639 --> 00:00:21.299
enthusiasts.

00:00:21.299 --> 00:00:24.360
It's cool to see all the variations.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:32.520
I'm excited to lean into the P word and go deep on Python.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:33.599
Just a little background.

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:36.000
My name is Michael Chow.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.919
I did a PhD in cognitive psychology.

00:00:38.919 --> 00:00:45.160
I do open source data tools at posit, focused on Python tools.

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:50.919
And I have two beautiful cats, Bandit and Moondog.

00:00:50.919 --> 00:00:54.240
So those aren't related at all to the topic.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:01:00.200
What I want you to think about is when you start a data analysis in Python, if you're

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:06.000
like me, do you think about the question, what data frame do I use?

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.940
I think it's in R you usually kind of have it figured out, but in Python you have quite

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:12.680
a few options.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:20.320
So you could import pandas or you could import pollers or you could also bring in duckdb

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:23.000
and work that into your analysis.

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:25.160
And I find the options really exciting.

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:29.160
I really like to have a lot of different options for analysis.

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:33.120
But I also find parts of it really overwhelming.

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:39.160
And I think the reason is that depending on the data frame you use, everything changes.

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:43.320
So you have to go to a new documentation site.

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:47.959
All the operations are different, sometimes subtly different.

00:01:47.959 --> 00:01:54.239
So you might maybe start with pandas and go there and learn its methods.

00:01:54.239 --> 00:01:56.239
And then you might switch to pollers.

00:01:56.239 --> 00:01:58.800
I've really been enjoying pollers a lot.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:04.519
And you'll notice that it looks eerily similar to the panda site, except everything's slightly,

00:02:04.519 --> 00:02:07.599
ever so slightly different.

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:12.360
And let's just say you keep going and you decide to go with pandas.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:16.059
And you just want to concatenate a couple columns.

00:02:16.059 --> 00:02:23.419
So that means you want to take the strings in X and you just want to concatenate them

00:02:23.419 --> 00:02:29.619
with Y. You could use df.x.sdr.cat.

00:02:29.619 --> 00:02:32.419
Don't ask me to say that again.

00:02:32.419 --> 00:02:35.460
And pass it dfy.

00:02:35.460 --> 00:02:36.660
And that will concatenate it.

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:43.020
So you'll get two rows, A, C, B, D. I had to check that, but that's exactly what you'll

00:02:43.020 --> 00:02:44.500
get.

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:45.500
So great.

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:46.940
That's fine.

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:49.500
But then let's say you decide to use pollers.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:53.220
And you decide to do something a little bit similar.

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:56.699
And so you notice there's a concat method.

00:02:56.699 --> 00:02:59.940
So there, let's say you try the concat method.

00:02:59.940 --> 00:03:02.699
As it turns out, you'll get an error.

00:03:02.699 --> 00:03:06.139
And the reason is concat in pollers actually aggregates.

00:03:06.139 --> 00:03:11.380
So it sort of pastes all the letters in your series.

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:17.220
And actually, the argument you pass makes no sense to pollers, and it's mad at you.

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:22.899
I find this really, I actually love all the options they give me, but I find this switching,

00:03:22.899 --> 00:03:29.020
this sort of split-brain nature of working with data, really challenging in Python.

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:34.440
And leaning into the movie, everything everywhere all at once, I sort of, I want to try coining

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:36.139
a pattern for this.

00:03:36.139 --> 00:03:40.179
I think this is the everything bagel pattern.

00:03:40.179 --> 00:03:46.460
It's the pattern where you have a data tool, but you also want to kind of stuff in everything

00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:48.559
people might want to do with it.

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:52.820
So you take every possible method, and you add it on.

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:54.860
And I actually, again, I love options.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.820
I love that I can do a lot with it.

00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:02.179
But I find it really kind of overwhelming when I'm switching off between things, that

00:04:02.179 --> 00:04:07.080
I'm switching off kind of the whole world.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:08.380
I think one neat thing.

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:12.779
Oh, so just some, yeah, you can't really use pandas methods on pollers data.

00:04:12.779 --> 00:04:19.200
You can, but there's this interchange, and that's really vexing to me.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:20.700
So let's keep going, though.

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:24.540
I think one really neat thing, I've been using a lot of DuckDB, and I think the really neat

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:29.019
thing is you can run DuckDB on either pandas or pollers.

00:04:29.019 --> 00:04:30.700
You can just use DuckDB functions.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:36.899
DuckDB has its own docs, so it's not totally innocent from this, like, docs thing.

00:04:36.899 --> 00:04:39.500
But I really like using DuckDB.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:46.619
I find the one challenge is that I see people write a lot of SQL in Python strings.

00:04:46.619 --> 00:04:54.559
And so this is kind of a weird tradeoff if you're doing it in Python.

00:04:54.559 --> 00:05:00.980
So one really neat thing, I think, about Suba and DuckDB is you can use dplyr syntax to

00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:07.660
generate SQL for DuckDB, and you could still harness the power of the Duck.

00:05:07.660 --> 00:05:10.980
So in this case, you would do a little bit of setup.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:16.299
Right now, we're using SQLAlchemy to sort of create a connection to DuckDB.

00:05:16.299 --> 00:05:20.739
And then dplyr style, you would create a table.

00:05:20.739 --> 00:05:27.540
So this is similar to how dplyr connects to database tables.

00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:30.339
And then you can feed it into something like mutate.

00:05:30.339 --> 00:05:39.500
And it might actually give you back that exact same sort of SQL, that concat statement.

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:46.059
So I really like this approach because I get the syntax and the grammar of dplyr, but the

00:05:46.059 --> 00:05:48.940
power of DuckDB.

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:53.899
And I think especially in Python, that's really helpful to have that escape hatch.

00:05:53.899 --> 00:05:58.779
You might notice, though, there's one weird thing that's going to be a big topic here,

00:05:58.779 --> 00:06:01.739
which is this is a quirk.

00:06:01.739 --> 00:06:05.579
Suba actually is translating pandas methods.

00:06:05.579 --> 00:06:11.260
I think going back to that Duck situation, I don't want to add new methods at all.

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:16.660
Like you already have half a dozen Duck sites to worry about.

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:24.339
In my mind, Suba was originally built on pandas to manipulate pandas data.

00:06:24.339 --> 00:06:26.540
And so it just used the pandas methods.

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:31.179
I didn't want to create a whole new Duck site for people.

00:06:31.179 --> 00:06:33.700
But it's a little bit weird when you're working with DuckDB.

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:38.459
Now if you think about it, if you're a person working with DuckDB, it's weird to be in the

00:06:38.459 --> 00:06:44.260
DuckDB Docs and then have to actually switch to pandas methods that get translated back

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:46.059
to DuckDB.

00:06:46.059 --> 00:06:52.500
I feel like it's the same sort of split-brained problem as the sort of pandas, polars, everything

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:55.660
bagel methods situation.

00:06:55.779 --> 00:07:02.220
So what I want to talk about today is an approach I've been working on called DuckOps, which

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:08.380
is the idea of what if you could just import the DuckDB functions into Python and just

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:10.100
use those?

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:16.059
Now it's sort of all DuckDB, and you don't have to worry about this weird translational

00:07:16.059 --> 00:07:17.059
Docs thing.

00:07:17.059 --> 00:07:23.779
You could hopefully stick mostly with the DuckDB Docs and still get dplyr syntax in

00:07:23.779 --> 00:07:25.420
Python.

00:07:26.179 --> 00:07:29.820
And I've been really enjoying this approach.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:33.820
So just to recap, I think you've heard a lot about DuckDB.

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:34.820
DuckDB is really neat.

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:35.820
It's fast.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:36.820
It can read all kinds of things.

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:42.619
It's got really cool cutting-edge SQL syntax that it's added.

00:07:42.619 --> 00:07:48.619
The idea with DuckOps is that you should be able to just read the DuckDB functions in

00:07:48.619 --> 00:07:50.380
and use them in Python.

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:53.579
And there are a lot of really neat advantages to that.

00:07:53.739 --> 00:07:59.459
And then Suba is the dplyr part of being able to mutate and filter and select.

00:07:59.459 --> 00:08:01.459
All right.

00:08:01.459 --> 00:08:07.739
But I want to really focus on this thing, this move from methods to functions.

00:08:07.739 --> 00:08:11.980
I think as our user, if there are a lot of our users in this room, you probably already

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:17.380
appreciate functions because it's most of what you use when you're analyzing data.

00:08:17.380 --> 00:08:23.540
But what if I told you the thing on the left, methods, are probably the dominant way of

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:26.220
working with data in Python.

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:30.739
So I want to focus on why this is a really big deal.

00:08:30.739 --> 00:08:33.739
And it goes back to this, the everything bagel.

00:08:33.739 --> 00:08:35.239
All right.

00:08:35.239 --> 00:08:41.859
So I'm going to talk about how functions are sort of alternative realities.

00:08:41.859 --> 00:08:45.919
And then I want to focus a little bit more on methods and some of their limits.

00:08:45.919 --> 00:08:50.739
And then some more advanced features that you can do with DuckDB.

00:08:50.739 --> 00:08:52.299
All right.

00:08:52.299 --> 00:08:56.059
So first, functions are alternative realities.

00:08:56.059 --> 00:09:01.380
In the movie Everything Everywhere All at Once, we follow a character, Evelyn, as she

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:04.179
experiences many different universes.

00:09:04.179 --> 00:09:08.099
In one, she has hot dogs for fingers.

00:09:08.099 --> 00:09:11.299
In another, she's a cat person.

00:09:11.299 --> 00:09:15.979
And in yet another, she's a rock on a mountain.

00:09:15.979 --> 00:09:21.780
And a big challenge is Evelyn finds these alternative realities overwhelming.

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:28.619
When you move through these different realities, you might feel a bit fractured and overwhelmed.

00:09:28.619 --> 00:09:31.940
Because there's a whole universe of alternatives out there.

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:37.299
And they can really creep up on you and get you.

00:09:37.299 --> 00:09:39.059
I think about it like this.

00:09:39.059 --> 00:09:42.299
I think that there are so many things you can do with data.

00:09:42.299 --> 00:09:45.179
And it's worth diving into every single one.

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:51.340
Whether it's like strings or dates or nested things, which is a crazy topic.

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:57.659
I think that there are a lot of talks at PositConf on these specific areas.

00:09:57.659 --> 00:10:02.020
We've heard talks about working with dates that are really in-depth.

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:08.940
And there's a library, StringR, just dedicated to string stuff.

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:10.559
So there's all these functions.

00:10:10.559 --> 00:10:14.520
There's all these sort of lives you can live in data analysis.

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:19.419
And I'm sure you know a datetime person who's gone weirdly deep into datetimes.

00:10:19.419 --> 00:10:24.219
And they're disheveled when they come out.

00:10:24.219 --> 00:10:28.739
They're ranting about, I don't know, epochs and different things.

00:10:28.739 --> 00:10:32.020
There are whole worlds out there.

00:10:32.020 --> 00:10:38.640
In DuckOps, each of these is just a submodule you can import from.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:40.520
And I think this is really helpful.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:45.400
It's dumb, but it's really helpful to explore and find the different things you might want

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:49.380
to use.

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:52.900
So I think a big advantage of all these functions is they're really easy to tinker with.

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:56.020
You can just import concat, and you can see what happens.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:59.619
So concat ABC is ABC.

00:10:59.619 --> 00:11:00.619
That's great.

00:11:00.619 --> 00:11:01.619
I love that.

00:11:01.619 --> 00:11:05.340
Concat with a polar series is a polar series.

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:09.059
That's pretty handy to figure out what's going to happen.

00:11:09.059 --> 00:11:15.159
One interesting thing is with a SUBA underscore, it returns a lazy expression.

00:11:15.159 --> 00:11:22.960
And you can use that inside these sort of, like, lazy queries in interesting ways.

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:26.880
Another nice thing about functions is you can just look up docs often.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:30.599
So from Python, I can just figure out what concat does.

00:11:30.599 --> 00:11:33.400
When concat's tucked inside a string, it's really hard to figure out.

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:38.080
You kind of have to go find other ways.

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:39.080
Functions are really discoverable.

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:40.159
I'm going to attempt to play this.

00:11:40.159 --> 00:11:43.799
I don't even know where my ‑‑ there it is.

00:11:43.799 --> 00:11:46.359
This is just showing, looking things up.

00:11:46.359 --> 00:11:50.840
It's not really fancy, but when you're in the middle of a data analysis, you kind of

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:53.739
want to know your options really fast.

00:11:53.739 --> 00:11:58.359
So this is not exciting at all, but it is exciting to me.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:12:05.640
All right, I don't know where ‑‑ I guess my cursor lives here now, so.

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:07.760
The other thing is functions work great programmatically.

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:12.559
So if you want to, say, change how concat works, so this is actually concat underscore

00:12:12.559 --> 00:12:15.799
WS, which is how db says with separator.

00:12:15.799 --> 00:12:19.119
I don't know why I put that in air quotes.

00:12:19.119 --> 00:12:22.000
You can modify the behavior of a function.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.960
So in Python, this is a partial.

00:12:23.960 --> 00:12:27.520
This is saying, like, the separator's always a dash.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:31.599
And now we have a dash concat, and that's all it does.

00:12:31.599 --> 00:12:34.679
It's dumb, but it works.

00:12:34.679 --> 00:12:36.919
We'll get into methods where it doesn't work in a little bit.

00:12:36.919 --> 00:12:40.219
So the thing is you can swap in alternatives.

00:12:40.219 --> 00:12:45.900
So here, if we don't want concat, we can just import a new concat from a new package, and

00:12:45.900 --> 00:12:50.340
suddenly we have another version.

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:54.539
So just to recap, you can really easily tinker across things.

00:12:54.539 --> 00:13:00.460
It's easy to discover functions, to program them, and to swap in alternatives.

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:07.820
In contrast, methods, the everything bagel pattern, methods are a bit tricky to work

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:08.820
with.

00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:11.979
So we've put everything on the data, and it's nice.

00:13:11.979 --> 00:13:15.739
You can look it up via a dot, but there are some downsides.

00:13:15.739 --> 00:13:17.760
One is that you end up with a lot of docs.

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:21.260
People tend to reproduce methods.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:27.460
The other is that if you wanted to put a concat, say, on a panda series, you would actually

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:30.640
have to do something really weird and kind of violent to it.

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:32.419
You would have to mutate it.

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:36.419
So you would just take the series, and you would actually just kind of shove concat in

00:13:36.419 --> 00:13:37.700
there.

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:38.700
It's a really weird.

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:44.179
I don't think the owner of a class can really put methods on it in a normal way.

00:13:44.179 --> 00:13:46.380
The other thing is you can't change the first argument.

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:49.659
A method is like a function that loves its first argument.

00:13:49.659 --> 00:13:52.140
So a panda series, isn't it weird?

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:56.859
You can concat the string ABC to something, but on a panda series, you actually can't

00:13:56.859 --> 00:14:00.460
do that, because the series is always the first thing.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:05.380
So it's surprisingly hard.

00:14:05.380 --> 00:14:07.260
The last is you can't really program.

00:14:07.260 --> 00:14:11.520
So we saw you could partial the concat function.

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:15.380
This isn't really easy or fun or desirable with methods.

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:20.159
You just sort of can't do it.

00:14:20.159 --> 00:14:26.299
A lot of people will say, method apologists will say, what about method chains?

00:14:26.299 --> 00:14:27.900
They're super convenient.

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:34.739
You can take this Dagwood sandwich on the left, this deep nested set of function calls,

00:14:34.739 --> 00:14:37.340
and you can turn it into this nice chain.

00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:38.340
I agree.

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:41.700
I think that's really important.

00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:47.900
Suba tries to work around this with function change, just this pipe syntax.

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:51.179
So you can pipe functions into each other.

00:14:51.179 --> 00:14:56.099
So it's tough, because method chaining is a part of Python, so you get it in the language.

00:14:56.099 --> 00:15:02.219
But this is an attempt to kind of get the same thing with functions.

00:15:02.219 --> 00:15:05.780
Just to recap, methods are a little bit hard to discover.

00:15:05.780 --> 00:15:08.020
Everybody has their own docs for methods.

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:11.059
A function just has one doc string.

00:15:11.059 --> 00:15:16.979
Alternatives, you need to actually mutate classes to add new methods onto them.

00:15:16.979 --> 00:15:20.520
And the last is method chains are a really handy thing.

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:24.700
Hopefully pipe chains, this concept can get you pretty close.

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:26.380
All right.

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:30.700
So just to have a deeper, I'm going to gloss, go through these very fast.

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:36.099
I think DuckDB, just to summarize, has some really cool syntax and some really advanced

00:15:36.099 --> 00:15:37.859
SQL it can do.

00:15:37.859 --> 00:15:42.900
So here, this is actually that dash arrow is a lambda.

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:46.099
There's all these interesting constructs they have.

00:15:46.099 --> 00:15:50.739
I think in DuckOps, a big challenge is going to be reproducing that.

00:15:50.739 --> 00:16:00.299
So here, we can run this list filter function, and we do have syntax for lambdas.

00:16:00.299 --> 00:16:02.580
And this is also used in the dplyr across.

00:16:02.580 --> 00:16:05.739
So a lot of the same stuff is reused.

00:16:05.739 --> 00:16:10.299
Secondly, would you rather have string R functions?

00:16:10.299 --> 00:16:11.539
That's actually pretty doable.

00:16:11.539 --> 00:16:16.359
Like you could create, hopefully it's not called string R pi, but with just functions,

00:16:16.359 --> 00:16:18.760
you could create alternative functions.

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:22.260
You could create string R. Or we could do it as a team.

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:24.340
All right.

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:27.099
So just to recap, DuckDB is incredible.

00:16:27.099 --> 00:16:28.099
It's fast.

00:16:28.099 --> 00:16:29.700
It can read all kinds of files.

00:16:30.099 --> 00:16:32.099
It has cutting-edge SQL syntax.

00:16:32.099 --> 00:16:36.739
DuckOps is this experiment in trying to pull the DuckDB functions out.

00:16:36.739 --> 00:16:42.299
And I really want to make the point, hopefully, that these functions are really useful.

00:16:42.299 --> 00:16:45.380
And as functions, there's a lot you can do with them.

00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:50.380
And then last, Suba aims to be a dplyr port to Python, and hopefully can let you build

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:56.419
up your DuckDB query and use it programmatically from Python.

00:16:56.419 --> 00:17:03.099
So I want to thank everybody that helped, Krista Adams, who designed the hex sticker,

00:17:03.099 --> 00:17:09.339
which will make a proper hex and not a squiggly hex, I swear it, Chris Gardillo, Anthony Baker,

