00:17:26.739 --> 00:17:28.739
We have a few questions.

00:17:28.739 --> 00:17:33.579
So the Zen of Python says there should only be one way to do it.

00:17:33.579 --> 00:17:38.140
Would you say that the Python data ecosystem fails to live up to that philosophy?

00:17:38.140 --> 00:17:39.140
Yeah.

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:42.260
I think that that's an interesting mantra.

00:17:43.260 --> 00:17:50.140
I mean, that's the funny thing about methods is that your first attempt at a method lives

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:53.300
forever because it lives on your data.

00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:58.219
So I would almost flip it and say with methods, you only get one attempt.

00:17:58.219 --> 00:18:05.180
But actually, if you look at the history of the tidyverse, packages like stringr and lubridate

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:10.619
and all the failed versions of those things, it's really clear that R innovated through

00:18:10.619 --> 00:18:18.500
alternatives and decoupling of the functions that can act on data from the data itself.

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:19.500
But I agree.

00:18:19.500 --> 00:18:23.579
It would be nice to have one way to do things, but sometimes you've got to like search around,

00:18:23.579 --> 00:18:24.579
you know?

00:18:24.579 --> 00:18:25.579
Sure.

00:18:25.579 --> 00:18:26.579
Sure.

00:18:26.579 --> 00:18:29.180
Does Suba support polars and pandas?

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:33.060
I mean, we're just, we're basically barnacling on DuckDB at this point.

00:18:33.060 --> 00:18:36.380
I think I would love to support polar's expressions, actually.

00:18:36.380 --> 00:18:41.300
I think similar to extracting out DuckDB functions, it would be cool to just work directly

00:18:41.300 --> 00:18:48.859
on polar's expressions, but I think it would involve a little bit of rust scuba diving.

00:18:48.859 --> 00:18:50.060
One more question.

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:54.060
Is there a data world that's not currently supported by DuckOps that you'd like to see

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:55.060
in there in the future?

00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:56.060
A data?

00:18:56.060 --> 00:19:01.540
Oh, I mean, there's all the like geo functions and I mean, it seems like there's a ton of

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:02.739
stuff in DuckDB.

00:19:02.739 --> 00:19:08.020
So this was really a first pass to see what it would look like and how it would feel to

00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:09.020
run.

00:19:09.020 --> 00:19:10.699
I almost feel like I'm really sold on the feel.

00:19:10.699 --> 00:19:12.219
I like the functions.

00:19:12.219 --> 00:19:17.699
And so now I'm really interested in exploring how do we really flesh that out and see what

00:19:17.699 --> 00:19:23.140
it looks like to just try to cover as much as possible if it's useful.

00:19:23.140 --> 00:19:24.140
Thank you very much.

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:26.020
Let's thank Michael and all of our other speakers again.

